Nasarawa State has recorded its first case of Coronavirus (COVID-19), since the outbreak of the pandemic in January. Governor Abbdullahi Sule, broke the news yesterday during a security meeting at the Conference Hall of Government House, Lafia. The governor said a lady from Garaku, in Kokona local government area of the state, who went to Kano on a business trip, imported the virus to the state. According to him, the lady returned recently from Kano, developed some strange signs and was taken into isolation before she tested positive. “Four of the five and the most important of them, being the celebrated lady that was said to have ran away from Abuja and isolated in Akwanga, their results came out yesterday and they were negative. “However, we were not that lucky with the fifth case and so for the first time, we had a lady that tested in Kokona local government area and it was positive. “She is currently quarantined at the Dalhatu Araf Specialist Hospital (DASH), Lafia, where we have good facility for such victims and she will be taken good care of. “We have also isolated the family of the lady so that we can conduct proper tests to ensure that none of her family is infected. “That somebody is infected does not mean that person is finished. Most of those who have been infected have actually recovered,” he said. While appreciating the people of the state, COVID-19 Task Force Committee and the security agencies as well as the traditional institutions, the governor said his appreciation will not be complete without thanking local government authorities, media and other stakeholders in the state for the show of support and cooperation in the fight against COVID-19.